26
00:01:19,599 --> 00:01:20,479
Thank you very much.

27
00:01:22,128 --> 00:01:27,434
Glad to see that our lead designer has a platinum.

28
00:01:27,434 --> 00:01:31,297
So before we start, let's start with a reminder of what

29
00:01:31,297 --> 00:01:32,138
Horizon is.

30
00:01:32,138 --> 00:01:34,740
And here's our E3 trailer from 2016.

31
00:01:57,560 --> 00:02:02,281
We know we weren't the first ones here.

32
00:02:02,281 --> 00:02:12,883
Our stories speak of the ones that came before.

33
00:02:12,883 --> 00:02:14,284
The Old Ones.

34
00:02:14,284 --> 00:02:21,725
The world of the Old Ones was so different than ours.

35
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:26,427
They had built incredible cities.

36
00:02:27,647 --> 00:02:34,409
With towers that reached the stars.

37
00:02:34,409 --> 00:02:35,409
But a darkness came.

38
00:02:35,409 --> 00:02:40,211
And their cities turned to graves.

39
00:02:40,211 --> 00:02:55,055
And without them, the land started to change.

40
00:02:55,055 --> 00:02:57,076
Their great cities faded away.

41
00:03:01,657 --> 00:03:10,461
And in their place came new life.

42
00:03:10,461 --> 00:03:25,448
Over time, one by one, the tribes came to these lands.

43
00:03:25,448 --> 00:03:27,309
Some, small and humble.

44
00:03:27,309 --> 00:03:31,251
Some, powerful as kings.

45
00:03:32,785 --> 00:03:36,850
They say my tribe was the first.

46
00:03:36,850 --> 00:03:37,911
The first to hunt.

47
00:03:37,911 --> 00:03:41,354
The first to raise our bows.

48
00:03:41,354 --> 00:03:47,040
For this world was never ours.

49
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:49,543
We've always shared it.

50
00:03:49,543 --> 00:03:55,089
A dangerous balance between man and machine.

51
00:04:06,858 --> 00:04:07,718
There's the herd.

52
00:04:07,718 --> 00:04:08,798
It goes on and on and on.

53
00:04:08,798 --> 00:04:12,820
So today I'm going to talk a little bit about the

54
00:04:12,820 --> 00:04:13,840
Our Direction Horizon.

55
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:16,241
But before we go there, I want to talk about the

56
00:04:16,241 --> 00:04:18,321
idea behind Horizon.

57
00:04:18,321 --> 00:04:19,482
We get this question a lot.

58
00:04:19,482 --> 00:04:21,142
Where's the orange of the idea?

59
00:04:21,142 --> 00:04:24,683
Where does this idea of a young girl hunting robo dinosaurs

60
00:04:24,683 --> 00:04:27,664
in a post-apocalyptic world come from?

61
00:04:27,664 --> 00:04:31,866
And that all started in 2010, when our studio asked us, the

62
00:04:31,866 --> 00:04:34,407
development staff, to pitch ideas for a new game.

63
00:04:35,927 --> 00:04:37,929
Before that time, we had worked on Killzone

64
00:04:37,929 --> 00:04:39,110
for almost a decade.

65
00:04:39,110 --> 00:04:40,652
And Killzone, for those who know,

66
00:04:40,652 --> 00:04:42,654
is a first-person shooter that is set

67
00:04:42,654 --> 00:04:44,976
in a dark and dystopian future.

68
00:04:44,976 --> 00:04:47,378
And while Killzone had been moderately successful,

69
00:04:47,378 --> 00:04:49,180
it never really was a great hit.

70
00:04:49,180 --> 00:04:52,203
So after about six of these titles, we needed to reconsider.

71
00:04:52,203 --> 00:04:55,987
Is this really the best way to use our development team's

72
00:04:55,987 --> 00:04:57,208
time, talent, and effort?

73
00:04:58,688 --> 00:05:02,309
And some of you may have heard of the term franchise fatigue.

74
00:05:02,309 --> 00:05:04,490
So unlike movie franchises, games

75
00:05:04,490 --> 00:05:05,970
tend to get better with their sequels.

76
00:05:05,970 --> 00:05:09,471
And that is basically because over time

77
00:05:09,471 --> 00:05:12,332
and over multiple titles, development teams really

78
00:05:12,332 --> 00:05:13,212
gets much better.

79
00:05:13,212 --> 00:05:15,873
They get better at understanding the technology.

80
00:05:15,873 --> 00:05:17,833
They get better at understanding each other.

81
00:05:17,833 --> 00:05:19,834
And they get better at understanding what makes

82
00:05:19,834 --> 00:05:20,734
their particular game tick.

83
00:05:22,097 --> 00:05:24,639
So unless your company has a very high turnover and staff,

84
00:05:24,639 --> 00:05:28,801
it's usually the case that the same people, the same team,

85
00:05:28,801 --> 00:05:30,442
work on sequel after sequel.

86
00:05:30,442 --> 00:05:33,344
Sometimes, as in our case, maybe more than a decade.

87
00:05:33,344 --> 00:05:34,845
And then at some point, that team

88
00:05:34,845 --> 00:05:36,166
gets tired after overworking it.

89
00:05:36,166 --> 00:05:41,229
Although your knowledge and the team synergy and the skill sets

90
00:05:41,229 --> 00:05:47,613
are all at peak performance, the results are sort of diminishing.

91
00:05:47,613 --> 00:05:48,934
So after all, how many different games

92
00:05:48,934 --> 00:05:50,855
can you make about a bunch of space Nazis

93
00:05:50,855 --> 00:05:51,715
with red glowing eyes?

94
00:05:53,190 --> 00:05:55,151
So let's reboot completely.

95
00:05:55,151 --> 00:05:56,131
Let's start from scratch.

96
00:05:56,131 --> 00:05:59,772
Let's take all of our learnings, the learnings of my first IP,

97
00:05:59,772 --> 00:06:04,673
and see what we can do when we all start from scratch.

98
00:06:04,673 --> 00:06:07,234
So first, let me tell you a little bit about Sony in itself.

99
00:06:07,234 --> 00:06:09,755
Sony has quite a unique structure.

100
00:06:09,755 --> 00:06:11,435
It's fundamentally bottom-up.

101
00:06:11,435 --> 00:06:13,276
So Sony doesn't really tell the studios

102
00:06:13,276 --> 00:06:15,096
what kind of games they make.

103
00:06:15,096 --> 00:06:17,257
They let that figure out themselves.

104
00:06:17,798 --> 00:06:19,680
Of course, there's a little bit of typecasting going on.

105
00:06:19,680 --> 00:06:22,804
Naughty Dog tends to basically make action shooters.

106
00:06:22,804 --> 00:06:24,726
And Goliath used to make first-person shooters.

107
00:06:24,726 --> 00:06:27,048
Polyphony makes racing games.

108
00:06:27,048 --> 00:06:29,330
The God of War team makes God of War.

109
00:06:29,330 --> 00:06:31,252
And so.

110
00:06:32,118 --> 00:06:34,939
So figuring out what we're going to make is really up to us.

111
00:06:34,939 --> 00:06:37,620
And in Guerrilla's case, we apply that structure all the

112
00:06:37,620 --> 00:06:39,541
way down to the core of our process.

113
00:06:39,541 --> 00:06:41,762
So we go to our own development staff and ask them

114
00:06:41,762 --> 00:06:45,404
what kinds of games they would like to make.

115
00:06:45,404 --> 00:06:47,225
But before you try this at home, it's probably good to

116
00:06:47,225 --> 00:06:50,487
understand that this level of creative freedom often needs a

117
00:06:50,487 --> 00:06:51,847
lot of guidance to be successful.

118
00:06:53,199 --> 00:06:55,600
I'm not sure how many of you are familiar with this diagram.

119
00:06:55,600 --> 00:06:58,081
It's the double diamond design process.

120
00:06:58,081 --> 00:07:00,322
It gets used a lot in complicated processes

121
00:07:00,322 --> 00:07:02,644
like service design.

122
00:07:02,644 --> 00:07:03,784
And to be honest, Becky.

123
00:07:04,349 --> 00:07:05,730
We didn't actually know that this was a thing

124
00:07:05,730 --> 00:07:07,191
until we had made the game.

125
00:07:07,191 --> 00:07:09,653
And then we heard about it, and we were like, oh, that's

126
00:07:09,653 --> 00:07:11,735
kind of what we did.

127
00:07:11,735 --> 00:07:13,796
So in hindsight, we did this instinctively.

128
00:07:13,796 --> 00:07:15,377
But it makes a lot of sense.

129
00:07:15,377 --> 00:07:17,579
So if you think about it, the pitch process

130
00:07:17,579 --> 00:07:20,661
that I'm about to describe is this discover phase.

131
00:07:20,661 --> 00:07:23,764
And you want to go as wide as possible with the ideas

132
00:07:23,764 --> 00:07:24,244
that you gather.

133
00:07:25,315 --> 00:07:27,996
And then as you go forward, you go narrow again

134
00:07:27,996 --> 00:07:29,577
as you try to define a core of a game.

135
00:07:29,577 --> 00:07:32,778
And then you go sort of broad again, wide again.

136
00:07:32,778 --> 00:07:35,519
It's sort of this cycle of adding new ideas

137
00:07:35,519 --> 00:07:36,799
and then subtracting the bad ideas.

138
00:07:36,799 --> 00:07:38,980
But even in the discover phase, you

139
00:07:38,980 --> 00:07:40,921
need to have some sort of direction

140
00:07:40,921 --> 00:07:42,802
because you need to go somewhere.

141
00:07:42,802 --> 00:07:45,743
Otherwise, you just get this explosion of creativity.

142
00:07:45,743 --> 00:07:48,123
And then it's really hard to define it down again

143
00:07:48,123 --> 00:07:50,924
to what the focus is of something.

144
00:07:50,924 --> 00:07:53,005
So I'm going to describe a little bit,

145
00:07:53,005 --> 00:07:54,966
making how we focused our creativity.

146
00:07:56,075 --> 00:07:58,357
We put together this brief that went to everybody

147
00:07:58,357 --> 00:08:00,859
in an entire company with a very specific mission.

148
00:08:00,859 --> 00:08:03,841
Develop an epic and cinematic character-driven game universe

149
00:08:03,841 --> 00:08:06,023
with intense action-packed gameplay,

150
00:08:06,023 --> 00:08:09,326
strong storytelling set in a distinct and rich universe.

151
00:08:09,326 --> 00:08:12,048
Yeah, good luck with that.

152
00:08:12,048 --> 00:08:14,230
So it's a really, really big statement.

153
00:08:14,230 --> 00:08:16,892
And it's actually pretty open.

154
00:08:16,892 --> 00:08:18,913
What it mostly says is don't come up

155
00:08:18,913 --> 00:08:21,375
with a mobile puzzle game.

156
00:08:23,062 --> 00:08:26,205
And because we have all this creative autonomy as a studio,

157
00:08:26,205 --> 00:08:27,686
we felt an enormous responsibility

158
00:08:27,686 --> 00:08:30,249
to do this right, not just creatively, but also

159
00:08:30,249 --> 00:08:32,311
strategically and commercially.

160
00:08:32,311 --> 00:08:35,114
So the nine-page briefing that we sent out,

161
00:08:35,114 --> 00:08:38,958
we concluded a whole broad range of topics.

162
00:08:38,958 --> 00:08:40,799
We didn't exclude any genre, but there

163
00:08:40,799 --> 00:08:43,823
were a couple of considerations that people needed to take.

164
00:08:43,823 --> 00:08:45,304
First of all, Begi, you know.

165
00:08:46,103 --> 00:08:47,644
Think about this from Sony perspective,

166
00:08:47,644 --> 00:08:49,884
maybe what is missing in their portfolio.

167
00:08:49,884 --> 00:08:52,925
And of course, maybe one thing that was missing

168
00:08:52,925 --> 00:08:54,045
was RPG and action RPG.

169
00:08:54,045 --> 00:08:56,486
And there were other considerations like,

170
00:08:56,486 --> 00:08:58,727
okay, we're good at some things.

171
00:08:58,727 --> 00:08:59,987
We have really good tech.

172
00:08:59,987 --> 00:09:02,708
We have good experience making with combat mechanics.

173
00:09:02,708 --> 00:09:04,508
We're good at making pretty arts.

174
00:09:04,508 --> 00:09:07,009
We have maybe a very good team of concept artists

175
00:09:07,009 --> 00:09:08,389
and a very good design team as well.

176
00:09:09,100 --> 00:09:12,942
But, you know, what can we do, maybe, with all these things that we've learned doing Killzone

177
00:09:12,942 --> 00:09:16,725
and come up with something, maybe, that uses or that leverages that knowledge

178
00:09:16,725 --> 00:09:19,847
without, maybe, just doing the same thing over and over again?

179
00:09:19,847 --> 00:09:23,410
And, of course, maybe we discuss other things as well, like, you know, market saturations,

180
00:09:23,410 --> 00:09:26,792
certain trends that were appearing, a whole bunch of different things

181
00:09:26,792 --> 00:09:28,413
that people could take into consideration.

182
00:09:29,887 --> 00:09:31,788
But mostly we asked them to think really big.

183
00:09:31,788 --> 00:09:33,750
The ambition for this new concept

184
00:09:33,750 --> 00:09:36,512
was to create a world that would be rich enough

185
00:09:36,512 --> 00:09:38,273
to explore in not just a series of games,

186
00:09:38,273 --> 00:09:40,935
but potentially also books and movies and onwards.

187
00:09:40,935 --> 00:09:43,597
Make you really think about franchise building instead

188
00:09:43,597 --> 00:09:44,999
of making just a single game idea.

189
00:09:44,999 --> 00:09:48,962
In total, we received about 30 to 40 pitches.

190
00:09:48,962 --> 00:09:52,244
This is just a very small sample of what we could still find.

191
00:09:52,244 --> 00:09:55,187
And so what was kind of.

192
00:09:55,763 --> 00:10:00,314
All it is, we didn't really specifically ask them to come up with ideas that were as

193
00:10:00,314 --> 00:10:01,577
opposite as possible from Killzone,

194
00:10:01,577 --> 00:10:04,684
but it's more something that sort of naturally came out of the process.

195
00:10:06,725 --> 00:10:10,106
And many of the pitches that we got, they hit on recurring notes.

196
00:10:10,106 --> 00:10:13,507
There were certain themes that we all gravitated towards.

197
00:10:13,507 --> 00:10:16,468
So, very clearly we were done with dystopian worlds

198
00:10:16,468 --> 00:10:19,609
full of glass and steel and concrete and bullets.

199
00:10:19,609 --> 00:10:23,010
And instead we wanted to build very lush and very rich worlds.

200
00:10:23,010 --> 00:10:25,670
I guess making sort of like, that's what franchise fatigue does.

201
00:10:25,670 --> 00:10:27,111
You can sort of want to make the other thing.

202
00:10:28,390 --> 00:10:31,492
But thankfully, we weren't really done with robots and mechs.

203
00:10:31,492 --> 00:10:36,656
We love that, we love a healthy dose of cool science fiction machines.

204
00:10:36,656 --> 00:10:39,759
But mostly we wanted to create something that was very unique.

205
00:10:39,759 --> 00:10:42,501
Something that has a positive tone to it.

206
00:10:42,501 --> 00:10:48,646
Something that felt very fresh, something that would be eye-catching, evocative, and

207
00:10:48,646 --> 00:10:51,409
mostly something that would stand out in the marketplace.

208
00:10:51,409 --> 00:10:53,270
And Horizon clearly stood out.

209
00:10:55,906 --> 00:10:57,506
from all the different concepts that were pitched.

210
00:10:57,506 --> 00:11:00,728
It was by far the favorite pitch among our own staff.

211
00:11:00,728 --> 00:11:03,208
And also, when we showed a couple of concepts

212
00:11:03,208 --> 00:11:04,689
to our colleagues at Sony,

213
00:11:04,689 --> 00:11:06,609
everybody said like, make this one.

214
00:11:06,609 --> 00:11:07,890
Making it sort of, it's weird

215
00:11:07,890 --> 00:11:10,131
and you're probably gonna fail,

216
00:11:10,131 --> 00:11:14,052
but you know, it's at least something new.

217
00:11:14,052 --> 00:11:16,533
So, what was it about Horizon that drew people in?

218
00:11:17,282 --> 00:11:19,664
Now, to some degree, we're still trying to figure that out.

219
00:11:19,664 --> 00:11:21,966
But we've got a couple of ideas.

220
00:11:21,966 --> 00:11:24,328
First of all, it had a lot of very contrasting elements,

221
00:11:24,328 --> 00:11:28,691
lots of juxtapositions that created intrigue and tension.

222
00:11:28,691 --> 00:11:31,873
So let's take a look at some of Verizon's many themes.

223
00:11:31,873 --> 00:11:35,736
First of all, it is a world where the flow of time

224
00:11:35,736 --> 00:11:37,097
appears to have been reversed.

225
00:11:37,097 --> 00:11:39,519
We've got a primitive age that has come

226
00:11:39,519 --> 00:11:40,940
after an age of high technology.

227
00:11:40,940 --> 00:11:44,443
And it's a world where the world of science

228
00:11:44,443 --> 00:11:46,525
has become the world of mythology and magic.

229
00:11:48,410 --> 00:11:51,314
And it's a world that questions the definition of life as we know it,

230
00:11:51,314 --> 00:11:54,338
where the artificial has become the natural.

231
00:11:54,338 --> 00:12:00,246
Now, usually going for high-concept science fiction is a very, very hard sell.

232
00:12:01,574 --> 00:12:03,914
But thankfully we got some help from James Cameron.

233
00:12:03,914 --> 00:12:07,075
In 2009, Avatar came out and it showed the whole world

234
00:12:07,075 --> 00:12:09,756
that the audience are still interested

235
00:12:09,756 --> 00:12:11,776
in very high concept science fiction.

236
00:12:11,776 --> 00:12:12,936
But in order to succeed,

237
00:12:12,936 --> 00:12:15,937
it needs to deliver something new and fresh.

238
00:12:15,937 --> 00:12:18,938
Now, Avatar, although it's a science fiction movie,

239
00:12:18,938 --> 00:12:20,218
it's actually a back to nature story.

240
00:12:20,218 --> 00:12:21,879
It's about a space faring civilization

241
00:12:21,879 --> 00:12:24,359
that clashes with the tribal inhabitants

242
00:12:24,359 --> 00:12:26,320
of a far away world.

243
00:12:26,780 --> 00:12:30,463
And it's a world where they celebrate this.

244
00:12:30,463 --> 00:12:32,144
They celebrate the magic of nature.

245
00:12:32,144 --> 00:12:34,946
So it's science fiction, but it's very relatable,

246
00:12:34,946 --> 00:12:36,127
and it's also very relevant.

247
00:12:36,127 --> 00:12:39,010
It asks a couple of important questions,

248
00:12:39,010 --> 00:12:41,952
like whether technology and nature are opposing forces.

249
00:12:41,952 --> 00:12:44,034
In the years before Avatar, there

250
00:12:44,034 --> 00:12:47,917
was a sort of reassurgence in the appreciation

251
00:12:47,917 --> 00:12:48,958
of the natural world.

252
00:12:48,958 --> 00:12:51,240
You may remember the Planet Earth series,

253
00:12:51,240 --> 00:12:53,301
the ones about the oceans, a whole bunch

254
00:12:53,301 --> 00:12:56,023
of these very lush, beautifully made documentaries.

255
00:12:56,673 --> 00:12:59,353
And ironically, it was actually new technologies and film

256
00:12:59,353 --> 00:13:01,754
technology that made these things possible.

257
00:13:01,754 --> 00:13:04,635
