00:40:37,455 --> 00:40:42,319
So it's not really art imitating life, it's art imitating technology that's imitating life.

763
00:40:42,800 --> 00:40:50,342
So it seems very logical that our very advanced robots would sort of converge to the shapes

764
00:40:50,342 --> 00:40:51,943
that we see in nature as well.

765
00:40:51,943 --> 00:40:56,905
If you think about it, wheels could have evolved in nature, but only if roads would have been

766
00:40:56,905 --> 00:40:59,326
a naturally occurring feature as well.

767
00:40:59,326 --> 00:41:03,467
But in a world where you only have mountains and tree stumps lying around, it makes a lot

768
00:41:03,467 --> 00:41:04,708
more sense to make it have legs.

769
00:41:05,463 --> 00:41:08,747
We also basically asked them if nature could be improved upon.

770
00:41:08,747 --> 00:41:15,956
Are there any design mistakes or evolutionary processes that didn't go to the most optimal form?

771
00:41:15,956 --> 00:41:18,298
Are there any sub-optimal solutions in nature?

772
00:41:18,925 --> 00:41:21,667
And they explain that internal skeletons is one,

773
00:41:21,667 --> 00:41:22,568
if you think about it.

774
00:41:22,568 --> 00:41:25,530
So all the soft tissue is on the outside,

775
00:41:25,530 --> 00:41:27,271
and then your hardest part is on the inside.

776
00:41:27,271 --> 00:41:28,632
This doesn't really make a lot of sense,

777
00:41:28,632 --> 00:41:30,094
because it's just too fragile.

778
00:41:30,094 --> 00:41:32,095
And also, if you break one arm, that's done.

779
00:41:32,095 --> 00:41:34,217
In nature, that's pretty much game over.

780
00:41:34,217 --> 00:41:34,757
You're dead.

781
00:41:34,757 --> 00:41:38,560
So why put all this soft, vulnerable tissue

782
00:41:38,560 --> 00:41:40,622
on the outside, and then create these sort

783
00:41:40,622 --> 00:41:42,303
of single points of failure?

784
00:41:42,303 --> 00:41:44,625
Is there a better solution for that?

785
00:41:44,625 --> 00:41:46,227
Yes, nature has better solutions for that.

786
00:41:47,342 --> 00:41:49,744
So exoskeletons, basically, are much more sturdier.

787
00:41:49,744 --> 00:41:52,386
You have the protective aspects on the outside.

788
00:41:52,386 --> 00:41:54,608
It's just, you know, if humans would look like this,

789
00:41:54,608 --> 00:41:56,850
they would be a lot less attractive to each other,

790
00:41:56,850 --> 00:41:58,391
I guess.

791
00:41:58,391 --> 00:42:02,114
And so we started to use these concepts of biomimetics,

792
00:42:02,114 --> 00:42:06,558
artificial pneumatic muscles, algorithmically generated

